62.name: HIPAA/HITECH Act
62.description: Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act, Title A.XIII of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009.
62.tooltip: HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) and the HITECH (Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health) act affect "covered entities" that access, maintain, retain, modify, record, store, destroy, or otherwise hold, use, or disclose unsecured protected health information. Click to review the US Department of Health & Human Services website for more information and click here for the definition of a "covered entity”.

64.name: GLB Act
64.tooltip: The Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act (GLB) requires financial institutions (companies that offer consumers financial products or services like loans, financial or investment advice, or insurance) to explain their information-sharing practices to their customers and to safeguard sensitive data. See the Bureau of Consumer Protection section of the FTC's website to learn more.

66.name: Connecticut (Insurance)
66.description: Applicable to licensees and registrants of the Connecticut Insurance Department.
66.tooltip: The State of Connecticut Insurance Department places requirements on all regulated entities in Connecticut, including insurance producers, public adjusters, bail bond agents, appraisers, certified insurance consultants, casualty claim adjusters, property and casualty insurers, life and health insurers, health care centers, fraternal benefit societies, captive insurers, utilization review companies, risk retention groups, surplus line companies, life settlement companies, preferred provider networks, pharmacy benefit managers, and medical discount plans. See the bulletin to learn more.

69.name: California (Health)
69.description: Regulator for clinics, health facilities, home health agencies, or hospices licensed pursuant to Section 1204, 1250, 1725 or 1745 of the California Health and Safety Code.
69.tooltip: The California Health and Safety Code places requirements on certain licensed health facilities. See the California Office of Privacy Protection to learn more.

70.name: FERPA
70.description: The Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) (20 U.S.C. § 1232g; 34 CFR Part 99) is a Federal law that protects the privacy of student education records. The law applies to all schools that receive funds under an applicable program of the U.S. Department of Education.
70.tooltip: FERPA is the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act, a Federal law that protects the privacy of student education records. The law applies to all schools that receive funds under an applicable program of the U.S. Department of Education. See the US Department of Education to learn more.

71.name: FISMA
71.description: The Federal Information Security Management Act of 2002 ("FISMA", 44 U.S.C. § 3541, et seq.) is a United States federal law enacted in 2002 as Title III of the E-Government Act of 2002 (Pub.L. 107-347, 116 Stat. 2899) applicable to all Federal agencies.
71.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves information collected or maintained by or on behalf of a U.S. Federal Agency; or information systems used or operated by a U.S. Federal Agency, or on behalf of a Federal Agency by a contractor or other organization. Click to review the Federal Information Security Management Act (FISMA) and OMB M-17-12, Preparing for and Responding to a Breach of Personally Identifiable Information.

72.name: PCI-DSS (Merchants)
72.tooltip: PCI-DSS is the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standards, developed and managed by the PCI Security Standards Council. The Council's five founding global payment brands -- American Express, Discover Financial Services, JCB International, MasterCard Worldwide, and Visa Inc. -- have agreed to incorporate the standards as the technical requirements of each of their data security compliance programs. The standard applies to all merchants that process any card branded with the logo of one of the card brands. Click here to learn more.

73.name: PCI-DSS (Issuers)
73.tooltip: PCI-DSS is the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standards, developed and managed by the PCI Security Standards Council. The Council's five founding global payment brands -- American Express, Discover Financial Services, JCB International, MasterCard Worldwide, and Visa Inc. -- have agreed to incorporate the standards as the technical requirements of each of their data security compliance programs. The standard applies to all organizations that issue payment cards branded with the logo of one of the card brands. Click here to learn more.

75.name: FINRA
75.description: Financial Industry Regulatory Authority ("FINRA"). It oversees the 4500+ registered brokerage firms in the US.
75.tooltip: FINRA is the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority, which oversees the 4500+ registered brokerage firms in the US. Click to review the FINRA website and the Cybersecurity Guidance for more information.

76.name: US Dept of Treasury
76.tooltip: The US Department of the Treasury directive applies to all bureaus, offices, and organizations in the Department of the Treasury, including the offices of Inspectors General within the Department. See the directive to learn more.

81.name: FCC
81.tooltip: FCC is the Federal Communications Commission, an independent United States government agency charged with regulating interstate and international communications by radio, television, wire, satellite and cable. See http://www.fcc.gov to learn more. Select this regulator if you are a Telecommunications Carrier regulated by the FCC, and the incident relates to an unauthorized disclosure or breach of Customer Proprietary Network Information (“CPNI”). Click to access the Act and Regulation.

82.name: OMB
82.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves information collected or maintained by or on behalf of a U.S. Federal Agency; or information systems used or operated by a U.S. Federal Agency, or on behalf of a Federal Agency by a contractor or other organization. Click to review the Federal Information Security Management Act (FISMA) and OMB M-17-12, Preparing for and Responding to a Breach of Personally Identifiable Information.

87.name: FTC (Health)
87.description: The Federal Trade Commission's Health Breach Notification Rule applies to vendors of personal health records and related entities, which are not subject to HIPAA/HITECH.
87.tooltip: Select FTC Health as a regulator if you are a vendor of personal health records or a related entity. This is NOT for HIPAA-covered entities or business associates. For further information, review the Rule or Complying with the FTC’s Health Breach Notification Rule section on FTC's website.

88.name: Data Breach Best Practices
88.tooltip: Data Breach Best Practices prescribe suggested non-regulatory activities for responding to breaches of PII.

89.name: NACHA
89.description: NACHA manages the development, administration, and governance of the ACH Network, the backbone for the electronic movement of money and data.
89.tooltip: NACHA manages the development, administration, and governance of the ACH Network, the backbone for the electronic movement of money and data. See the NACHA website to learn more.

90.name: Intermediate Processing
90.description: Internal use only for intermediate processing.

91.name: New York City
91.description: Law applicable to entities operating businesses requiring a license.
91.tooltip: The Administrative Code of the City of New York requires that certain businesses licensed in the city complete certain tasks when responding to incidents. Types of potentially affected businesses include (but may not be limited to) particular retail establishments, service providers, and vehicles/their operators.

92.name: CMS
92.description: Center for Medicare and Medicaid Services of the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services
92.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves information collected or maintained by or on behalf of a U.S. Federal Agency; or information systems used or operated by a U.S. Federal Agency, or on behalf of a Federal Agency by a contractor or other organization. Click to review the Federal Information Security Management Act (FISMA) and OMB M-17-12, Preparing for and Responding to a Breach of Personally Identifiable Information.

93.name: OCC
93.description: Office of the Comptroller of the Currency of the U.S. Department of the Treasury
93.tooltip: The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) is the primary federal regulator for all national banks and federal savings association. See the OCC website to learn more.

95.name: FDIC
95.tooltip: The Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) is the primary federal regulator of banks that are chartered by the states that do not join the Federal Reserve System. See the FDIC website to learn more.

96.name: Federal Reserve
96.description: Board of Governors of the U.S. Federal Reserve System
96.tooltip: The Federal Reserve has primary supervisory authority for state banks that elect to become members of the Federal Reserve System (state member banks). Click to review the Federal Reserve website for more information.

127.name: Montana (Insurance)
127.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a licensee or an insurance-support organization that conducts business in Montana, and you own or license computerized data that includes personal information. Click here to view the Montana’s Insurance Security Breach Law.

128.name: Ohio (Insurance)
128.tooltip: The Ohio Superintendent of Insurance places requirements on persons and organizations holding a license or certificate of authority from the Ohio Superintendent of Insurance to conduct business in the state. Click here to learn more or click to view the bulletin.

129.name: Rhode Island (Insurance)
129.tooltip: Select this Regulator if you are a licensee subject to the jurisdiction of the Rhode Island Department of Business Regulation. Click here to view the Regulation.

130.name: Wisconsin (Insurance)
130.tooltip: The Wisconsin Office of the Commissioner of Insurance places requirements on insurance licensees operating in the state. Click here to learn more.

131.name: Fannie Mae
131.tooltip: Fannie Mae is a government-sponsored enterprise chartered by Congress to keep money flowing to mortgage lenders, to help strengthen the U.S. housing and mortgage markets, and to support affordable home ownership. Fannie Mae has oversight responsibilities for mortgage lenders and servicers. Click here to review the Fannie Mae website for more information.

132.name: Virginia (Health)
132.tooltip: The state of Virginia has issued a regulation related specifically to the breach of medical information which imposes requirements on any authority, board, bureau, commission, district or agency of the Commonwealth or of any political subdivision of the Commonwealth, including cities, towns and counties, municipal councils, governing bodies of counties, school boards and planning commissions; boards of visitors of public institutions of higher education; and other organizations, corporations, or agencies in the Commonwealth supported wholly or principally by public funds. Click here to learn more.

133.name: Bank Secrecy Act
133.tooltip: The Bank Secrecy Act, enforced by the US Department of the Treasury, requires financial institutions to help prevent money laundering by keeping records of transactions. Click here to review the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network's page for more information.

134.name: Texas (Health)
134.tooltip: For purposes of breach response, Texas persons/organizations that are covered entities as defined by HIPAA/HITECH 45 C.F.R. Section 160.103 are also covered entities as defined by this Texas Health and Safety Code § 181.004. Click here to learn more.

135.name: Alberta
135.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the collection, use, or disclosure of personal information or personal employee information by a private sector organization in Alberta. Click to review the Act or the Regulation.

136.name: New Brunswick (Health)
136.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the collection, use or disclosure of individually identifiable personal health information that is in the custody or under the control of a custodian in New Brunswick. Please click to review the Act or the Regulation.

137.name: Newfoundland and Labrador (Health)
137.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves personal health information that was collected, used or disclosed by a custodian, or in the custody or control of a custodian, in both the public and private sectors in Newfoundland and Labrador. Click to review the Act and Regulation.

138.name: Ontario (Health)
138.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an Ontario custodian of individually identifiable health information that in involved in an incident of theft, loss, or unauthorized access or disclosure of such information. Click here to view the Personal Health and Information Act and the Regulation.

139.name: Manitoba (Health)
139.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the unauthorized collection, use disclosure or disposal of personal or personal health information. Such activity is "unauthorized" if it is not permitted by the Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act (FIPPA) or the Personal Health Information Act (PHIA). For assistance to public bodies and trustees in managing a privacy breach, see the Manitoba Ombudsman Key Steps in Responding to Privacy Breaches under FIPPA and PHIA. When notifying affected individuals see the Privacy Breach Notification Letter Checklist. When notifying the Manitoba Ombudsman see the Privacy Breach Reporting Form.

148.name: Texas person/entity/state agency
148.tooltip: Select this regulator either if: (i) you are a person/entity who conducts business in Texas, and the incident affects non-Texas residents; or (ii) if you are a Texas State Agency, that owns, licenses or maintains computerized data that includes sensitive personal information. Click to view the Texas security breach notification requirements here, and click here to view the specific requirement for a security breach by Texas State Agencies.

156.name: United Kingdom
156.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves: (1) the processing information by a controller or processor established in the United Kingdom; or (2) the personal data of a United Kingdom resident is processed in the context of offering goods or services (whether or not for payment), or the monitoring of the resident's behavior in the United Kingdom. Please click here to view the Data Protection Act 2018 and here to view the UK GDPR.

157.name: SEC
157.tooltip: The SEC is the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, which protects investors, maintains fair, orderly, and efficient markets, and facilitates capital formation. See http://www.sec.gov to learn more.

158.name: Italy (Banking Sector)
158.tooltip: Select Italy (Banking Sector) as a regulator if the incident is associated with processing of information by banks established in Italy. Click here to access the regulation in its entirety.

159.name: Australia
159.tooltip: Select Australia as a regulator if the incident is associated with 1) the processing of information in Australia by an Australian entity or 2) the processing of information belonging to an Australian citizen or resident outside of Australia by an entity doing business in Australia or collecting or holding information in Australia. The foregoing only applies to organizations with annual turnover of more than AU$3 million. They also apply, regardless of annual turnover, to all private sector health service providers, to organisations that buy and sell information without the individual’s consent, and contracted Commonwealth service providers in relation to their contractual activities. Click here to access the regulation and here or here for further guidance.

160.name: China
160.tooltip: Select this regulator if your organization is a Network Operator as defined by China’s Cybersecurity Law. Click here to view the Cybersecurity Law of 2016 (Only Available in Chinese), here to view the PFI Specification (GB/T 35273—2020) (Only Available in Chinese) and here to review the website of the National People’s Congress for further information.

161.name: Hong Kong
161.tooltip: Enable Hong Kong as a regulator if the incident is 1) associated with the processing of information in Hong Kong by a Hong Kong entity or 2) if a Hong Kong entity has experienced a breach. Click here to access the regulation and here to access guidance document.

162.name: Indonesia (electronic service providers)
162.tooltip: Select Indonesia (Electronic Service Providers) as a regulator if you are an Electronic Service Operator subject to Indonesia’s Government Regulation No. 71 of 2019 (“GR 71/2019”). Click here to review GR 71/2019 (Only available in Indonesian) or here to review Minister of Communication and Informatics Regulation No. 20 of 2016 regarding Personal Data Protection in Electronic Systems (Only available in Indonesian).

163.name: Japan
163.tooltip: Select Japan as a regulator if the incident involves the handling of personal information by a business operator located in Japan, or if it involves a business operator who is not located in Japan but handles personal information to offer goods or services to a person in Japan. Click here to access the Act and here to access the PPC website for further guidance.

164.name: New Zealand
164.tooltip: Select New Zealand as a regulator if you are: 1) a New Zealand agency whether or not in New Zealand in relation to personal information collected or held; 2) an overseas agency in relation to any action taken in the course of carrying on business in New Zealand in respect of personal information collected or held by oversees agency; or 3) an individual who is not ordinarily a resident in New Zealand, in relation to any action taken in respect of personal information collected by individual while present in New Zealand, regardless of where the information is subsequently held by individual or where the individual to whom the information relates is, or was, located; or personal information held by individual while present in New Zealand (but not collected by individual while present in New Zealand), regardless of where the individual to whom the information relates is, or was, located. For a New Zealand agency or an overseas agency, it does not matter where the personal information is, or was, collected by the agency; or where the personal information is held by the agency; or where the individual concerned is, or was, located. Click here to access the Privacy Act 2020, here to access the Privacy Commissioner: Responding to Privacy Breaches and here to access the Commissioner website.

165.name: Philippines
165.tooltip: Select Philippines as a regulator if the incident is associated with 1) the processing of information in the Philippines or 2) the processing of information belonging to a Philippine citizen or resident outside of the Philippines by an entity doing business in the Philippines or collecting or holding information in the Philippines. Click here for general information. To access the Act and Implementing Regulation (scroll to The Data Privacy Act and its IRR > scroll to The Data Privacy Act of 2012 and select either Web or PDF to open). To access the NPC Circular (scroll to Memorandum Circulars).

166.name: Singapore
166.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves unauthorized access, collection, use, disclosure, copying, modification or disposal, or similar risk of personal data and you are an individual, company, association or body of persons, corporate or unincorporated, whether or not: (a) formed or recognized under the law of Singapore; or (b) resident, or having an office or a place of business, in Singapore. Click here to access the 2012 PDPA, click here to access the 2020 Amendments, click here to access guidance on the 2020 Amendments, click here to access the Personal Data Protection Regulations 2021 (Notification of Data Breaches), and here to view the PDPC website.

167.name: South Korea
167.tooltip: Select South Korea as a regulator if the incident involves the direct or indirect processing of personal information by a public institution, legal person, organization, or individual that is established in South Korea, or processes the personal information of data subjects in South Korea. For the Personal Information Protection Act in Korean, click here (to access, click link and open link in first line (No. 16930)); or for an English translation, click here (to access, click link > scroll to “Recently Updated” > Click “Personal Information Protection Act [Enforcement Date: 5. Aug 2020.] (No. 16930)). Click here to access the Enforcement Decree No.30509 (Only available in Korean) (To access, click link and open link in third line (No. 30509)). See the Personal Information Protection Commission website for further information.

168.name: Taiwan
168.tooltip: Enable Taiwan as a regulator if the incident is associated with the processing of information in Taiwan by a Taiwan entity. Click here to access the Personal Data Protection Act and here to the Enforcement Rules.

169.name: EU Telecoms and ISPs
169.tooltip: Enable this regulator if your organization is a provider of publicly available electronic communications services in the EU. Click here for access to the Regulation, and here for the Directive.

171.name: Argentina
171.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident is associated with legal domicile or offices or branches in Argentina, whose data are treatment referred to this law. Click here to access the regulation, and here to access the directorate.

172.name: Bahamas
172.tooltip: Enable Bahamas as a regulator if the incident is associated with a) a data controller established in The Bahamas and the data are processed in the context of that establishment; or (b) a data controller that is not established in The Bahamas but uses equipment in The Bahamas for processing the data otherwise than for the purpose of transit through The Bahamas. Click here to access the regulation and definitions, and here to access the security breach guidance.

173.name: Colombia
173.tooltip: Select Colombia as a regulator if the incident involves the processing of personal data made in Colombia or when a foreign data controller is subject to Colombian regulations due to international treaties and regulations. Click here to access the regulation, here to access the guidance, and see the RNBD website for further information (Available only in Spanish).

174.name: Costa Rica
174.tooltip: Select Costa Rica as a regulator if the incident is associated with the processing of information in Costa Rica, or when an entity processing data is subject to Costa Rican regulations due to international treaties and regulations. Click here to access the law and relevant definitions, and here to access the regulation.

175.name: Mexico
175.tooltip: Enable Mexico as a regulator if the incident involves the processing of personal data by: (a) a data controller established in Mexico; (b) a data processor, regardless of its location, that is processing personal data on behalf of a data controller established in Mexico; (c) a data controller that is not established in Mexico, but is subject to Mexican laws due to contractual obligations or international law; or (d) a data controller not established in Mexico, but using means located in Mexico to process personal data (unless such means are used for transit purposes only). Click here to access the federal law, and here to access the regulation of the federal law.

176.name: Uruguay
176.tooltip: Select this regulator if the breach is associated with an entity established in Uruguay and processes data in Uruguay; or if an entity is established outside of Uruguay but uses means located in that country for data processing (unless for transit purposes only). Data processing is defined as systematic operations and procedures, whether automated or not, that allow personal data to be processed, as well as their transfer to third parties through communications, consultations, interconnections or transfers. Click here to access regulation 18-331 (only available in Spanish), here to access regulating decree 64/020 (only available in Spanish), and here to access the regulating decree 414/009. For further information, please click here to view the URCDP website.

179.name: France (Remote Payment Cards)
179.tooltip: Enable France (Remote Payment Cards) as a regulator if the incident is associated with an entity processing remote payment card transactions that is established on French territory; or established outside of the EU but processing remote payment card transactions in a French territory (unless for transit purposes only). Click here for the regulation, and here for the guidance documentation.

180.name: UK (Financial Sector)
180.tooltip: Select UK (Financial Sector) if the incident is associated with a financial firm regulated by the Prudential Regulatory Authority (PRA) or the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA); this includes all UK and overseas branches and representative offices of that firm (whether or not those branches or offices carry on any regulated activities.) Please click here to view the Data Protection Act 2018 and here for the rule.

181.name: Dubai
181.tooltip: Select Dubai as a regulator if you are a Controller or Processor incorporated in the DIFC, regardless of whether the Processing takes place in the DIFC or not; if you are a Controller or Processor, regardless of its place of incorporation, that Processes Personal Data in the DIFC as part of stable arrangements, other than on an occasional basis. This Law applies to such Controller or Processor in the context of its Processing activity in the DIFC (and not in a Third Country), including transfers of Personal Data out of the DIFC. Processing "in the DIFC" occurs when the means or personnel used to conduct the Processing activity are physically located in the DIFC, and Processing "outside the DIFC" is to be interpreted accordingly. Processing is defined as “any operation or set of operations performed upon Personal Data, whether or not by automated means, such as collection, recording, organization, structuring, storage and archiving, adaptation or alteration, retrieval, consultation, use, disclosure by transmission, dissemination, transfer or otherwise making available, alignment or combination, restricting (meaning the marking of stored Personal Data with the aim of limiting Processing of it in the future), erasure or destruction.” Click here to access the Data Protection Law, and here to access the Commissioner of Data Protection’s Guidance. Click here to see the Dubai International Financial Centre (DIFC) website.

182.name: South Africa
182.tooltip: Select South Africa as a regulator if the incident is associated with an entity established in South Africa and processing data in South Africa; or an entity established outside of South Africa that is processing data in South Africa (unless for transit purposes only). Processing is defined as, "any operation of activity or any set of operations, whether or not by automatic means, concerning personal information, including – (a) the collection, receipt, recording, organisation, collation, storage, updating or modification, retrieval, alteration, consultation, or use; (b) dissemination by means of transmission, distribution or making available in any other form; or (c) merging, linking, as well as restriction, degradation, erasure or destruction of information". Click here to access the regulation and here to view the Information Regulator website.

183.name: Peru
183.tooltip: Select Peru as a regulator if the incident involves the processing of data by an establishment in Peru, by a holder of a database in Peru or even where the holder of the database is not located in Peru but uses means located in Peru for the purposes of processing data. Click here to access the Law and Security Directive.

184.name: Arkansas (Mortgage Bankers and Loan Officers)
184.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a licensee of the Arkansas Securities Department, defined as a loan officer, mortgage broker, mortgage banker, or mortgage servicer who is licensed under the Arkansas Fair Mortgage Lending Act. Click here to access the Act, and here to access the rules of the Act.

185.name: NCUA
185.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a federally insured credit union subject to the jurisdiction of the National Credit Union Administration (NCUA). Click here to access the law and here to access the NCUA website for additional information.

186.name: California (Insurance)
186.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an admitted insurer, insurance producer, or insurance support organization subject to the California Department of Insurance. Click here to access the Notice.

188.name: Mexico (Payment Card Networks)
188.tooltip: Select Mexico (Payment Card Networks) if the breach is related to processing data within payment card networks in Mexico, and your organization is regulated by the Bank of Mexico and the National Banking and Securities Commission ("Comision Nacional Bancaria y de Valores"). Click here to access the regulation in its entirety. See the CNBV website for further information.

189.name: Ghana
189.tooltip: Select Ghana as a regulator if the incident is associated with an entity established [see section 45.3 of the Act for types of entities that are considered "established"], in Ghana and the data is processed in Ghana; or an entity established outside of Ghana but uses equipment or a data processor conducting business in Ghana to process the data, or processing is in respect of information which originates partly or wholly from this country. This Act does not apply to data that is processed in Ghana for solely for transit purposes. Click here to access the regulation and here to access the DPC Data Protection Principles.

190.name: DARS/Dept of Defense
190.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves information collected or maintained by or on behalf of a U.S. Federal Agency; or information systems used or operated by a U.S. Federal Agency, or on behalf of a Federal Agency by a contractor or other organization. Click to review the Federal Information Security Management Act (FISMA) and OMB M-17-12, Preparing for and Responding to a Breach of Personally Identifiable Information.

192.name: Washington (Insurance)
192.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a licensee of the Washington State Office of the Insurance Commissioner, and the incident involves private consumer information of Washington residents. Click here to view Washington’s Insurance security breach notification requirements.

194.name: Arkansas (Insurance)
194.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a legal entity engaged in the business of insurance, including without limitation an individual, corporation, association, partnership, reciprocal exchange, interinsurer, Lloyd's insurer, fraternal benefit society, agent, broker, and adjuster and if you are licensed or required to be licensed, authorized or required to be authorized, or registered or required to be registered by the Office of the Insurance Commissioner of Arkansas. This applies if you are a licensed insurer, health maintenance organization, or other insuring health entities regulated by the Insurance Commissioner of Arkansas, which governs the treatment of consumer financial and protected health information by the Arkansas Comprehensive Health Insurance Pool. Click here to learn more (scroll to Search/View Arkansas Code and Constitution of 1874 to launch LexisNexis > Title 23 Public Utilities and Regulated Industries > Subtitle 3. Insurance > Chapter 61 State Insurance Department > Subchapter 1-- General Provisions).

195.name: New York (Department of Financial Services)
195.tooltip:
(1) Select this regulator if you are a registered entity with the New York Department of Financial Services unless you have fewer than 10 employees, less than $5,000,000 in gross annual revenue in each of the last three fiscal years, less than $10,000,000 in year-end total assets, or if you do not have an information systems or nonpublic information. Click here to learn more.

(2) Select this regulator if you are a Consumer Reporting Agency (CRA) that reported on 1,000 or more New York consumers. Click here to learn more.

196.name: Illinois (State Agencies)
196.tooltip: Select this if you are an Illinois state agency that for any purpose, handles, collects, disseminates, or otherwise deals with nonpublic personal information. Click here to view the regulation.

197.name: New Hampshire (Insurance)
197.tooltip: Select this if you are a “Licensee” in New Hampshire, meaning all licensed insurers, producers and other persons licensed or required to be licensed or authorized or required to be authorized, or registered pursuant to the provisions of Title XXXVII. Click here to view the Regulation or here to view the definitions Ins. 3001.04 (q) and Ins 3701.02 (d).

219.name: Gibraltar
219.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves: (1) the processing of personal data in the context of the activities of an establishment of a controller or a processor in Gibraltar, regardless of whether the processing takes place in Gibraltar or not; or (2) the processing of personal data of data subjects who are in the Union (which, for the purpose of this paragraph, includes Gibraltar) by a controller or processor not established in the Union, where the processing activities are related to: (a) the offering of goods or services, irrespective of whether a payment of the data subject is required, to such data subjects in the Union; or (b) the monitoring of their behaviour as far as their behaviour takes place within the Union. Please click here to view the Data Protection Act.

220.name: Guernsey
220.tooltip: Select this Guernsey as a regulator if the incident involves: (1) the processing information by a controller or processor established in the Bailiwick; or (2) the personal data of a Bailiwick resident is processed in the context of offering goods or services (whether or not for payment), or the monitoring of the resident’s behavior in the Bailiwick. Please click here to view the Data Protection Act.

221.name: Isle of Man
221.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves: (1) the processing of personal data in the context of the activities of an establishment of a controller or a processor in the Island, regardless of whether the processing takes place in the Isle of Man or not; (2) processing of personal data of data subjects who are in the Union (which, for the purposes of this paragraph, includes the Isle of Man) by a controller or processor not established in the Union, where the processing activities are related to: (a) the offering of goods or services, irrespective of whether a payment of the data subject is required, to such data subjects in the Union; or (b) the monitoring of their behaviour as far as their behaviour takes place within the Union. Please click here to view the Data Protection Act.

222.name: Jersey
222.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the processing of information by a controller or processor: (1) established in Jersey; (2) not established in Jersey, but who uses equipment in Jersey to process data; (3) not established in Jersey, where the processing relates to data subjects who are in Jersey, and is for the purpose of offering goods or services, or monitoring their behavior. Please click to review the Data Protection Law, the Data Protection Regulation, the Amended Data Protection Regulation, and the Breach Reporting Guidelines.

224.name: Alberta (Health)
224.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the collection, use or disclosure of individually identifiable health information that is in the custody or under the control of a custodian. Please click to review the Amended Health Information Act, or the Regulation and Amended Regulation.

225.name: Virginia (Income Tax Preparers)
225.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the return information of individual Virginia tax payers that is maintained by an income tax preparer. Click here to view the Act.

226.name: PIPEDA
226.tooltip: Select this regulator: (1) if the incident involves personal information collected or disclosed in Canada by a private sector organization in the course of a commercial activity; or (2) if it involves personal information collected in Canada by a private sector organization that is about an employee and it was collected or disclosed in connection with the operation of a federal work, undertaking or business. Please note, the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA) allows provincial governments to occupy their own fields of responsibility and pass their own privacy laws. This is done by exempting organizations from PIPEDA's application, if the organization is otherwise subject to a provincial law that has been declared substantially similar to PIPEDA. Please click to view PIPEDA, the Breach of Security Regulations, and the OPC's Guidance on Provincial Legislation Deemed Substantially Similar to PIPEDA.

227.name: Bermuda
227.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an organization that uses personal information in Bermuda. Click here to review Bermuda’s Personal Information Protection Act.

228.name: Hong Kong (Monetary Authority)
228.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a bank, restricted license bank or a deposit-taking company, regulated by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA). Click to review the Hong Kong Banking Ordinance, the HKMA’s Supervisory Policy Manual, and the HKMA’s Circular on Consumer Data Protection.

229.name: Cayman Islands
229.tooltip: Select this regulator if: (1) you are established in the Cayman Islands and process personal data in the context of your establishment; or (2) you are not established in the Cayman Islands, but you process personal data in the Cayman Islands. Click here to review the Cayman Islands’ Data Protection Act.

230.name: Vermont (Data Brokers)
230.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a Data Broker, meaning a business that knowingly collects and sells or licenses to third parties, the brokered personal information of a Vermont resident with whom your business does not have a direct relationship. Click here to view the Act. Click here to view the Data Broker Guidance issued by the Vermont Attorney General.

231.name: China (Financial PBOC)
231.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a banking financial institution established in the People’s Republic of China. Click here to review Notice No. 17 [2011] of the People’s Bank of China – Notice of Strengthening the Work Relating to the Protection of Personal Financial Information by Financial Institutions in the Banking Industry and here to review the Notice No. 80 [2012] of the People's Bank of China – Urging Financial Institutions to Further Effectively Protect Clients' Personal Financial Information. Click here to review the PFI Specification JR/T 0171-2020.

232.name: Turkey
232.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the processing of personal data from Turkey. Click here to review the Data Protection Law No. 6698 of 2016, here for the Personal Data Protection Authority's (KKVK) Information Note on the Law on the Protection of Personal Data No. 6698 (Unofficial Translation), or here for the Personal Data Protection Board's Decision 2019/10 on the Process for Personal Data Breach Notification.

233.name: Mauritius
233.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are: (1) established in Mauritius and process personal data in the context of your establishment, or (2) not established in Mauritius, but you process personal data in Mauritius. Click here to review the Data Protection Act.

234.name: Israel
234.tooltip: Select this regulator if you own, manage or maintain a database containing personal information in Israel. Click to view the Protection of Privacy Law, 5741-1981 and the Protection of Privacy Regulations (Data Security) 5777-2017.

235.name: Qatar
235.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident relates to personal data in Qatar that is electronically processed or obtained, collected, or extracted by any other means in preparation for electronic processing by controllers, processors, and website operators. Click here to review Qatar's Law No. 13 of 2016 Concerning Protection of Personal Data.

236.name: Uganda
236.tooltip: Select this regulator if your organization is: (a) collecting, processing, holding or using personal data within Uganda; or (b) outside Uganda who collects, processes, holds, or uses personal data relating to Ugandan citizens. Click here to access The Data Protection and Privacy Act, 2019. Click here to access The Data Protection and Privacy Regulations, 2021 (UNOFFICIAL - DRAFT).

237.name: Serbia
237.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the processing of personal data in the context of the activities in Serbia of data controllers or data processors who have their registered seat or are resident in Serbia, regardless of whether the processing itself takes place in Serbia or not. You should also select this regulator if the incident involves the processing of data pertaining to data subjects residing in Serbia when such processing is both: (a) carried out by a data controller or a data processor which is located outside Serbia; and (b) related to: (1) offering goods or services to data subjects in Serbia; or (2) monitoring the behavior of data subjects. Please click here to view the regulatory text in Serbian or for an English translation, please click here.

238.name: Thailand
238.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves the processing of personal data in the context of the activities in Thailand of data controllers or data processors who have their registered seat or are resident in Thailand, regardless of whether the processing itself takes place in Thailand or not. You should also select this regulator if the incident involves the processing of data pertaining to data subjects residing in Thailand when such processing is both: (a) carried out by a data controller or a data processor which is located outside Thailand; and (b) related to: (1) offering goods or services to data subjects in Thailand; or (2) monitoring the behavior of data subjects. Click here to view the Personal Data Protection Act (Only available in Thai). For an unofficial English translation, please click here.

239.name: Maryland (Insurance)
239.tooltip: Select this as a regulator if you are governed by the Maryland Insurance Administration as an insurer, a nonprofit health service plan, a health maintenance organization, a dental organization, a managed care organization, a managed general agent, or a third-party administrator. Click here to view the Act (Click Articles > Insurance > Section 4-406. Breach of the security of a system) or click to view the bulletin.

240.name: California (CCPA)
240.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves California residents, you do business in California and collect Consumer Personal Information directly or indirectly, and you meet one or more of the following criteria: (a) have at least $25 million in annual revenue; (b) receive, buy, share for commercial purposes, alone or in combination, Personal Information of at least 50,000 California Consumers or devices; or (c) derive more than half of their annual revenue from the sale of Personal Information. Click here to view the California Consumer Privacy Act.

241.name: Montana (State Agencies)
241.tooltip: Select this regulator if the incident involves personal information collected by a Montana State Agency, or a third party that receives personal information from a Montana State Agency. Click here to review Montana's State Agency Protection of Personal Information Law.

242.name: Kenya
242.tooltip: Select Kenya as a regulator if the incident involves the processing of personal data: (a) entered in a record, by or for a data controller or processor, by making use of automated or non-automated means: provided that when the recorded personal data is processed by non-automated means, it forms whole or part of a filing system; or (b) By a data controller or processor who: (i) is established or ordinarily resident in Kenya and processes personal data while in Kenya; or (ii) not established or ordinarily resident in Kenya, but processing personal data or data subjects in Kenya. Click here to access the regulation.

243.name: Abu Dhabi Global Market
243.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an organization in Abu Dhabi Global Market processing personal data or involved in processing activities related to the offering of goods or services to data subjects in Abu Dhabi. Processing is defined as a "any operation or set of operations which is performed on Personal Data or on sets of Personal Data, whether or not by automated means, such as collection, recording, organisation, structuring, storage, adaptation or alteration, retrieval, consultation, use, disclosure by transmission, dissemination or otherwise making available, alignment or combination, restriction, erasure or destruction". Click here to view the Abu Dhabi Global Market Data Protection Regulations, 2021. To access the Data Protection Regulation of 2021 (select Commercial Legislation and Rules drop down > select Commercial Regulations and Rules > find Regulations > select Data Protection Regulations > Select Data Protection Regulations 2021). Click here to view the Office of Data Protection Breach Notification page or guidance.

244.name: Washington (State Agencies)
244.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are a Washington state agency that owns or licenses data that includes personal information or that maintains or possesses data that may include personal information that the agency does not own or license. Click here to view the regulation and here to view the amendment. For further information, please visit the Attorney General website and view the frequently asked questions for public agencies here.

245.name: North Macedonia
245.tooltip: Select this regulator if the data controller or processor is a public or private organization established in North Macedonia that processes personal data and is established in North Macedonia, regardless of whether the processing of personal data is performed in North Macedonia or not. You should also select this regulator if the incident involves processing of personal data of data subjects from North Macedonia when such processing is both (a) carried out by a data controller or processor located outside of North Macedonia; and (b) related to (1) offering of goods or services to data subjects; or (2) monitoring the behavior of personal data subjects, if any of the behavior takes place in Northern Macedonia. Click here to view the "Law on Personal Data Protection" (Only available in Macedonian) and here to view the North Macedonian Data Protection Authority ("DPA") Rulebook (Only available in Macedonian). For further information, please visit the DPA website.

246.name: South Korea (CSP)
246.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an information and communication service provider or a person who provides information or mediates the provision of information by using the telecommunications service of the telecommunications business for the purpose of profit and telecommunications business. Processing means the collection, generation, connecting, interlocking, recording, storage, retention, value-added processing, editing, searching, output, correction, recovery, use, provision, disclosure, and destruction of personal information and other similar activities. For the Personal Information Protection Act in Korean, click here (to access, click link and open link in first line (No. 16930)); or for an English translation, click here (to access, click link > scroll to “Recently Updated” > Click “Personal Information Protection Act [Enforcement Date: 5. Aug 2020.] (No. 16930)). Click here for the Network Act (Only Available in Korean) or here for the Presidential Decree No. 30691 (Only Available in Korean) (To access, click link and open document in fifth line, (No. 30691)).

247.name: Brazil
247.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an individual or public or private company carrying out a processing operation, regardless of the means, country of its headquarters or country where the data is located, as long as: the processing operation is performed within the country; ** the processing activity with the purpose of offering or providing goods or services, or processing of data from individuals located within the national territory; or the object personal data of processing was collected within the national territory. Data Processing is defined as every operation performed with the personal data, such as those related to the collection, production, receipt, classification, usage, access, reproduction, transmission, distribution, processing, filing, storage, disposal, assessment or control of information, modification, communication, transfer, broadcast or extraction. Click here to view the Lei Nº 13,709 (as amended by Lei Nº 13,853, only available in Portuguese).

248.name: Egypt
248.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are wholly or partially electronically processing under the possession of any data holder, controller or processor with regard to natural persons. Processing means any electronic or technological operation to write, collect, record, store, merge, present, transmit, receive, circulate, publish, delete, alter, modify, retrieve, or analyze personal data using any media or electronic and technological means whether wholly or partially. Personal data is any data related to an identified natural person, or to a natural person identifiable, directly or indirectly, by reference to any other data, such as name, voice, picture, identification number, online identifier, or any data that identifies psychological, health, economic, cultural or social identity. Click here to access the Personal Data Protection Law No. 151 of 2020 (Only available in Arabic).

249.name: Moldova
249.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an operator or a natural or legal person under public or private law, including the public authority, any other institution or organization which, individually or together with others, establishes the purposes and means of processing personal data and you are: (1) processing personal data carried out within the activities by operators located on the territory of the Republic of Moldova; (2) processing personal data carried out within the diplomatic missions and consular offices of the Republic of Moldova, as well as by other operators located outside the country, but on territories where the domestic law of the Republic of Moldova applies, under public international law; (3) processing personal data carried out by operators located outside the territory of the Republic of Moldova, using the means located on the territory of the Republic of Moldova, unless these means are used only for the purpose of transit on the territory of the Republic of Moldova of personal data are subject to that processing; or (4) processing personal data within the actions of prevention and investigation of crimes, the execution of convictions and other actions within the criminal or contravention procedure under the law. Processing of personal data means any operation or series of operations performed on personal data by automated or non-automated means, such as collection, registration, organization, storage, storage, restoration, adaptation or modification, extraction, consultation, use , disclosing by transmission, dissemination or in any other way, joining or combining, blocking, deleting or destroying. Click here to view Decision No. 1123, Republic of Moldova (14-12-2010) (Only available in Romanian), here to view Law No. 133 on the Protection of Personal Data (Only available in Romanian) and here to view the National Center for Personal Data Protection Data Breach Notification Portal for more information.

250.name: San Marino
250.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are 1) processing personal data wholly or partly by automated means and processing other than by automated means of personal data which form or intended to form part of a filing system (such processing is carried out by anyone established in San Marino or in a place subject to the sovereignty of San Marino); 2) not established in San Marino and processing personal data of data subjects in San Marino, where the processing activities are related to (a) the offering goods or services to such data subjects; or (b) the monitoring of the behaviour of such data subjects in so far as the behaviour taking place in San Marino; or 3) a natural person processing of personal data in the course of a purely personal or household activity, only if the data are intended for systematic communication or dissemination. Click here to review the San Marino Law no 171 of 21 December 2018 Protection of Natural Persons with Regard to the Processing of Personal Data and here to review the Model Form for Notification of Personal Data Breach to the Supervisory Authority (available only in Italian) and here to access the San Marino DPA website.

251.name: Barbados
251.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an organization established in Barbados processing personal data or involved in processing activities related to the offering of goods or services to data subjects in Barbados. Processing is defined as a "means to obtain, record or hold the information or data or carry out any operation or set of operations on the information or data, including the (a) organization, adaptation or alteration of the information or data; (b) retrieval, consultation or use of the information or data; (c) disclosure of the information or data by transmission, dissemination or otherwise making available; or (d) alignment, combination, blocking, erasure or destruction of the information or data." Click here to review The Barbados Data Protection Act, 2019.

252.name: Zambia
252.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are processing personal data performed wholly or partly by automated means; and any process otherwise by electronic means under the possession of data controller or processor relating to an identified or identifiable natural person. This Act does not apply to the processing of personal data by an individual for personal use. Click here to access the regulation.

253.name: Abu Dhabi Global Market (Organizations established before Feb 14, 2021)
253.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are an organization established before February 14, 2021, in Abu Dhabi Global Market processing personal data or involved in processing activities related to the offering of goods or services to data subjects in Abu Dhabi. Processing is defined as a "any operation or set of operations which is performed on Personal Data or on sets of Personal Data, whether or not by automated means, such as collection, recording, organisation, structuring, storage, adaptation or alteration, retrieval, consultation, use, disclosure by transmission, dissemination or otherwise making available, alignment or combination, restriction, erasure or destruction." Click here to view the Abu Dhabi Global Market Data Protection Regulations, 2021. To access the Data Protection Regulation of 2015 (select Commercial Legislation and Rules drop down > select Commercial Regulations and Rules > find Regulations > select Data Protection Regulations > Select Data Protection Regulations 2015). To access the Data Protection (Amendment) Regulation of 2018 follow the same steps > select Data Protection (Amendment) Regulation of 2018. Click here to view the Office of Data Protection Breach Notification page or guidance.

254.name: Rwanda
254.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are processing personal data performed wholly or partly by automated means; and any process otherwise by electronic or other means under the possession of data controller or processor relating to an identified or identifiable natural person. Click here to access the regulation.

255.name: Zimbabwe
255.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are processing personal data performed wholly or partly by automated means; and any process otherwise by electronic or other means under the possession of data controller or processor relating to an identified or identifiable natural person.

256.name: Cape Verde
256.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are processing personal data performed wholly or partly, with or without automated means; and any process otherwise by electronic or other means under the possession of data controller or processor relating to an identified or identifiable natural person. Click here to access the regulation.

257.name: Eswatini (Swaziland)
257.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are processing personal data performed wholly or partly by automated means; and use automated or non-automated means in Eswatini for forwarding personal information. Click here to access the regulation.

258.name: Bahrain
258.tooltip: Select this regulator if you are: (a) a natural person residing in or maintaining a place of business in Bahrain; (b) a legal person with a place of business in Bahrain; or (c) processing personal data by means located in Bahrain (unless the purpose of using such means is merely for transit data over Bahrain). Click here to access the law.

44.name: Personal Identification
44.description: This data type represent any data element or collection of data elements that could be used to identify people.

45.name: Personal Health Record (Electronic)
45.description: A personal health record is an electronic health record that can be drawn from multiple sources and that is managed, shared, and controlled by or primarily for the individual.

46.name: Third-Party Account Information
46.description: Any information about accounts housed at a financial institution other than this organization.

66.name: Other Information Relating to an Identified or Identifiable Person
